{{anthropology-stub}}

[[File:Altar twelve gods Louvre Ma666.jpg|thumb|300px|Although the ritual purpose of this 1st-century BC altar from [[Gabii]] is unclear, the twelve deities depicted correspond to the ''Dii Consentes'']]
The '''''Dii Consentes''''', also as '''''Di''''' or '''''Dei Consentes''''' (once '''''Dii Complices'''''<ref>[[Arnobius]] III.40</ref>), was a list of twelve major deities, [[List of Roman deities|six gods and six goddesses]], in the [[Religion in ancient Rome|pantheon of Ancient Rome]]. Their gilt statues stood in the [[Roman Forum|Forum]], later apparently in the [[Porticus Deorum Consentium]].<ref>[[Samuel Ball Platner]], ''The Topography and Monuments of Ancient Rome'' (1904), pp. 173–174.</ref>

The gods were listed by the poet [[Ennius]] in the late 3rd century BC in a paraphrase of an unknown Greek poet:<ref>Ennius, fragment 45 = [[Apuleius]], ''De deo Socratis'', 2.28–29.</ref>
:''[[Juno (mythology)|Juno]], [[Vesta (mythology)|Vesta]], [[Minerva]], [[Ceres (mythology)|Ceres]], [[Diana (mythology)|Diana]], [[Venus (mythology)|Venus]],''
:''[[Mars (mythology)|Mars]], [[Mercury (mythology)|Mercury]], [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]], [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]], [[Vulcan (mythology)|Vulcan]], [[Apollo]]''

[[Livy]]<ref>Livy, [[s:From the Founding of the City/Book 22#10|XXII.10.9]].</ref> arranges them in six male-female pairs: Jupiter-Juno, Neptune-Minerva, Mars-Venus, Apollo-Diana, Vulcan-Vesta and Mercury-Ceres. Three of the Dii Consentes formed the [[Capitoline Triad]]: Jupiter, Juno, and Minerva.

==Background==
The grouping of twelve deities has origins older than the [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] or Roman sources. The Greek grouping may have Anatolian, more precisely [[Lycia]]n origins. A group of twelve [[Hittite mythology|Hittite gods]] is known both from [[cuneiform]] texts and from artistic representation. The Hittite Twelve are all male, with no individualizing features. They have a possible reflex in a Lycian group of twelve gods in the [[Roman Empire]] period. By 400 BC, a precinct dedicated to twelve gods existed at the marketplace in [[Xanthos]] in Lycia.{{sfnp|Long|1987|pages=144-186}}

[[Herodotus]] also refers to a group of twelve gods in Egypt, but this finds no confirmation in [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] sources. The Greek cult of the [[Twelve Olympians]] can be traced to 6th century BC [[Athens]] and probably has no precedent in the [[Mycenaean period]]. The altar to the Twelve Olympians at Athens is usually dated to the [[eponymous archon|archonship]] of the younger Pesistratos, in 522/521 BC. By the 5th century BC there are well-attested [[cult (religious practice)|cults]] of the Twelve Olympians in [[Olympia, Greece|Olympia]] and at the [[Yoros Castle#History|Hieron]] on the [[Bosphorus]].{{sfnp|Long|1987|pages=144-186}}

The references to twelve [[Etruscan mythology|Etruscan deities]] are due to later Roman authors, writing long after [[Interpretatio graeca|the influence of the Greek pantheon]] had become dominant, and must be regarded with skepticism. [[Arnobius]] states that the [[Etruscans]] had a set of six male and six female deities which they called ''consentes'' and ''complices'' because they rose and set together, implying an [[astronomical]] significance, and that these twelve acted as councillors of Jupiter.{{sfnp|Long|1987|page=232}} Scholarly evaluation of this account is dependent on the hypothesis that the Etruscans originally immigrated to [[Italy]] from [[Anatolia]]. In this case, the Etruscan Twelve might have been cognate to the Hittite Twelve. It is, however, just as possible that the Etruscan Twelve were simply an adaptation of the Greek Twelve just like the Roman Twelve.{{sfnp|Long|1987|page=232}}

